h3. Problem Definition

[Database Setup for Oracle|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/database-setup-for-oracle-173821.html] has an instruction to grant predefined roles – {{CONNECT}}, {{RESOURCE.}} but these roles are not recommended by Oracle because they should be outdated in near future.
h3. Suggested Solution

Change the instruction to grant
 * {{CREATE SESSION}}
 (to replace the role in {{CONNECT}})
 * {{CREATE CLUSTER}}
 * {{CREATE INDEXTYPE}}
 * {{CREATE OPERATOR}}
 * {{CREATE PROCEDURE}}
 * {{CREATE SEQUENCE}}
 * {{CREATE TABLE}}
 * {{CREATE TRIGGER}}
 * {{CREATE TYPE}}
 (to replace the role in {{RESOURCE}})

h3. Why this is important

Because these predefined roles may not be created automatically as described in below.
 [Configuring Privilege and Role Authorization-- Predefined Roles in an Oracle Database Installation |https://docs.oracle.com/database/121/DBSEG/authorization.htm#DBSEG4414]
{quote}Note: Oracle recommends that you design your own roles for database security rather than relying on this role. This role may not be created automatically by future releases of Oracle Database.
{quote}

h3. Issue Summary

In Confluence, using the JIRA issue macro, if the user is searching for Alphanumeric key, the macro will automatically perform a search in the description and summary fields. (bug)

This is not the case for alphabetic keys, however. 
 # When the project key is alphabetic only(HLPD), and you typed in the key for tasks within the project such as HLPD-3555 the macro will automatically perform the following search:
{code:java}
key = HLPD-3555
{code}

 # When a project key is alphabetic only, and you typed the project key only. For example HLPD, the macro will automatically perform the following search:
{code:java}
summary ~ "HLPD" OR description ~ "HLPD" {code}

Based on the above, it should be the case that for alphanumeric keys, the behavior should be the same as the above.  
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # In JIRA, create a project that has alphanumeric key, for example:
{code:java}
NR5GX0A{code}

 # In Jira, create few tasks under the above project, so that the tasks have keys such as NR5GX0A-1, NR5GX0A-2.
 # In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A in the search field.
 # In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A-1 in the search field.

h3. Expected Results 
{quote}In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A in the search field.
{quote}
The result of the above should be that the macro performs the following search in JIRA
{code:java}
summary ~ "NR5GX0A" OR description ~ "NR5GX0A" {code}
{quote}In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A-1 in the search field.
{quote}
The result of the above should be that the macro performs the following search in JIRA
{code:java}
 key = NR5GX0A-1 {code}
h3. Actual Results
{quote}In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A in the search field.
{quote}
The result of the above should be that the macro performs the following search in JIRA
{code:java}
summary ~ "NR5GX0A" OR description ~ "NR5GX0A" {code}
{quote}In Confluence, using the Issue Macro, type in the NR5GX0A-1 in the search field.
{quote}
The result of the above should be that the macro performs the following search in JIRA
{code:java}
summary ~ "NR5GX0A-1" OR description ~ "NR5GX0A-1"  {code}
h3. Workaround

The only workaround here is to ensure that the user explicitly type the "key" filed in the Jira issue macro search. For example:
{code:java}
 key = NR5GX0A-1  {code}

